{"title":"How to watch Strade Bianche 2024","link":"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/how-to-watch-strade-bianche","date":1709315733000,"content":"<p><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a><br />\n<a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/how-to-watch-strade-bianche\">How to watch Strade Bianche 2024</a></p>\n\n<p>The <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/strade-bianche-all-you-need-to-know\" target=\"_blank\">Strade Bianche</a> men’s and women’s races will take place on Saturday 2nd March 2024, with the men’s race covering 215km and the women’s race over 136km.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>With this the 18th edition for the men and tenth for the women, it’s a race still in its infancy, but Strade Bianche has nonetheless already entered cycling folklore and makes for unmissable viewing thanks to an intriguing parcours across the picturesque Tuscany countryside, battling the unpaved white roads that dissect the many fields and vineyards.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"646\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/03/pidcock-strade-bianche-2023-970x646.jpeg\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/03/pidcock-strade-bianche-2023-970x646.jpeg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/03/pidcock-strade-bianche-2023-300x200.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/03/pidcock-strade-bianche-2023-768x512.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/03/pidcock-strade-bianche-2023-1536x1024.jpeg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/03/pidcock-strade-bianche-2023-2048x1365.jpeg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/03/pidcock-strade-bianche-2023-750x500.jpeg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/03/pidcock-strade-bianche-2023-1140x760.jpeg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/03/pidcock-strade-bianche-2023-465x310.jpeg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/03/pidcock-strade-bianche-2023-620x413.jpeg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/03/pidcock-strade-bianche-2023-350x233.jpeg 350w\" /><figcaption>Strade Bianche</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>While, for the purists at least, Strade Bianche isn’t <em>technically</em> a Classic, it stands alongside the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/all-you-need-to-know-about-the-classics-monuments-cobbles\" target=\"_blank\">early season northern Classics</a> in its mix of paved and unpaved surfaces and the variability of the weather conditions. Often, the race is on dry, dusty roads, but a bit of rain, <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/anna-van-der-breggen-strade-bianche\" target=\"_blank\">as in 2018</a>, can quickly turn them to mud, caking the riders.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Last year’s winners were Tom Pidcock – who went solo early on and just about held off the chasing group – and Demi Vollering, who, after a run-in with a horse, outsprinted teammate Lotte Kopecky for a big win and an awkward post-race celebration.</p>\n\n\n<div>\r\n                <div>\r\n                   <div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <h4><span>Related Posts</span></h4>\r\n                      </div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <div>\r\n                            <div>\r\n                            <article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/omloop-het-nieuwsblad-2024-tech-gallery\">Omloop Het Nieuwsblad tech gallery: Van Aert’s Cervélo Soloist, 30mm tyres, Lidl-Trek on tubs?</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n           